
#Automate Our Script using At or Crontab

#for only one time
 sumit@Sumit:~$ chmod +x ~/script/01_basic.sh
sumit@Sumit:~$ at 23:00 31 July 2025
warning: commands will be executed using /bin/sh
at Thu Jul 31 23:00:00 2025
at> <EOT>
job 2 at Thu Jul 31 23:00:00 2025
sumit@Sumit:~$ atq
2       Thu Jul 31 23:00:00 2025 a sumit


#repeating tak
 You're currently inside the crontab -e editor, which by default opens in nano (a text-based editor).

You’ve correctly written your cron job:

c
Copy code
0 23 31 7 * /home/sumit/script/01_basic.sh
Now, you just need to save and exit.

✅ How to Save and Exit in nano
Press Ctrl + O to write (save) the file
You'll see:

pgsql
Copy code
File Name to Write: /tmp/crontab.XXXXX/crontab-new
Press Enter to confirm

Press Ctrl + X to exit the editor

You’ll then see:

bash
Copy code
crontab: installing new crontab
This means your cron job is now scheduled.

✅ To Confirm
bash
Copy code
crontab -l
It should show:

bash
Copy code
0 23 31 7 * /home/sumit/script/01_basic.sh
